{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cec21cb9-5818-4e32-a7c8-42c686c820dc","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, look for:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** — macOS automatically generates these:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Files are named like `YourApp_<date>_<host>.crash` or `.ips`.\n\n2. **Core dumps** — disabled by default. To enable:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. Core files appear in `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n3. **Console.app** — Open it and check **Crash Reports** in the sidebar for a formatted view.\n\nSince `createdump` isn't bundled with NativeAOT apps, Apple's built-in crash reporter is your best bet. The `.crash`/`.ips` files include the stack trace, signal info, and loaded libraries.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ed65bc54-b7cb-497d-ae89-2ed7f217c5d7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.","outputTokens":266,"requestId":"764F:834FC:D9A3C7:100CF0A:69FE9218"},"id":"4c9c103b-efed-4021-bdac-b599f75f83b8","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:47:11.608Z","parentId":"be3700a7-a235-46c4-a5e7-ecb15e951b3d"}
